1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:05,519
[inquisitive] So Sam, what's the deal with slideSonnet? Tell me about it!

2
00:00:06,719 --> 00:00:09,011
[excited] Oh you're gonna LOVE this!

3
00:00:09,011 --> 00:00:13,722
It takes your plain-text slides and turns them into fully narrated VIDEOS.

4
00:00:13,722 --> 00:00:18,434
You just write slides, throw in some comments for narration, and SHAZZAM —

5
00:00:18,434 --> 00:00:19,389
you get an MP4!

6
00:00:20,589 --> 00:00:25,918
[skeptical] OK but WHY? ... Can't I just record myself talking over slides?

7
00:00:27,118 --> 00:00:31,493
[dry humor] Sure, if you ENJOY sitting in a quiet room with a mic,

8
00:00:31,493 --> 00:00:33,150
talking through EVERY ...

9
00:00:33,150 --> 00:00:35,869
SINGLE ... slide till you get it right...

10
00:00:37,069 --> 00:00:43,262
[sarcastic] And the BEST part — change one slide and you get to re-record it.

11
00:00:43,262 --> 00:00:45,193
EVERY... SINGLE... TIME.

12
00:00:46,393 --> 00:00:48,543
[enthusiastic] With slideSonnet,

13
00:00:48,543 --> 00:00:53,179
your narration is just text sitting next to the code for your slides!

14
00:00:53,179 --> 00:00:57,547
Edit a line, hit rebuild, DONE! No mic, no re-recording, no pain!

15
00:00:58,747 --> 00:01:03,188
[intrigued] Alright, you've got my attention. How does it ACTUALLY work?

16
00:01:04,388 --> 00:01:07,148
[confidently] Step one: write your slides.

17
00:01:07,148 --> 00:01:10,500
In Markdown or in LaTeX, whatever floats your boat!

18
00:01:11,700 --> 00:01:18,183
Step two: drop in "say" comments. Just text ... with the words you want spoken.

19
00:01:18,183 --> 00:01:19,824
That's LITERALLY it!

20
00:01:21,024 --> 00:01:24,286
[enthusiastic] Step three: run slidesonnet build.

21
00:01:24,286 --> 00:01:29,610
It does the speech synthesis, renders your slides, and stitches it ALL together.

22
00:01:29,610 --> 00:01:31,473
ONE command and you're done!

23
00:01:32,673 --> 00:01:35,364
[eager] OK I want to try it! What do I do?

24
00:01:36,564 --> 00:01:39,302
[confidently] Literally THREE commands.

25
00:01:39,302 --> 00:01:44,638
pip install, INIT to set up a project template, and BUILD to make the video.

26
00:01:44,638 --> 00:01:50,043
That's IT! [proudly] You'll have a narrated MP4 before your coffee gets cold!

27
00:01:51,243 --> 00:01:57,199
[surprised] Hold on — the narration is LITERALLY JUST a comment in the Markdown?

28
00:01:58,399 --> 00:02:02,172
[proudly] YEP! An HTML comment that starts with say colon.

29
00:02:02,172 --> 00:02:04,124
The text inside becomes audio.

30
00:02:04,124 --> 00:02:09,198
[excitement building] And here's the FUN part — what you're hearing RIGHT now?

31
00:02:09,198 --> 00:02:11,800
[enthusiastic] Written EXACTLY this way!

32
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,809
[curious] So where does all the CONFIG STUFF go?

33
00:02:16,809 --> 00:02:19,348
Voices, text-to-speech settings?

34
00:02:20,548 --> 00:02:24,259
[enthusiastic] The playlist file is slide sonnet dot yaml.

35
00:02:24,259 --> 00:02:27,971
It's got your text-to-speech backend, your voice mappings,

36
00:02:27,971 --> 00:02:30,786
pronunciation dictionaries — the WHOLE deal!

37
00:02:30,786 --> 00:02:35,073
[proudly] And slideSonnet finds it AUTOMATICALLY, so you hit build,

38
00:02:35,073 --> 00:02:37,057
and everything else JUST WORKS!

39
00:02:38,257 --> 00:02:39,497
[awe] Wait a SECOND!

40
00:02:39,497 --> 00:02:43,403
[in wonder] THIS is how we're using different voices RIGHT NOW?

41
00:02:44,603 --> 00:02:48,347
[playfully] YUP! You're alex, and I AM the default voice.

42
00:02:48,347 --> 00:02:51,172
You just STICK a voice parameter in the say

43
00:02:51,172 --> 00:02:53,865
comment and slideSonnet handles the rest!

44
00:02:53,865 --> 00:02:55,836
[proudly] Pretty SLICK, right?

45
00:02:57,036 --> 00:03:00,353
[curious] Can you do that thing where bullets pop in one at a time?

46
00:03:01,553 --> 00:03:02,819
[confidently] Oh YEAH!

47
00:03:02,819 --> 00:03:06,961
Just use star bullets instead of dashes and each one becomes a fragment!

48
00:03:08,161 --> 00:03:12,131
[enthusiastic] Every fragment gets its own sub-slide and narration. EASY!

49
00:03:13,331 --> 00:03:16,937
[enthusiastic] It ends up feeling JUST like a REAL talk —

50
00:03:16,937 --> 00:03:18,582
ideas building one by one!

51
00:03:19,782 --> 00:03:22,473
[wondering] What if I've got a slide that doesn't need any talking?

52
00:03:23,673 --> 00:03:28,695
[casually] Easy. Nonarration gives you a quiet pause — nice for title cards.

53
00:03:28,695 --> 00:03:33,586
And skip just HIDES the slide from the video completely. Great for drafts.

54
00:03:33,586 --> 00:03:35,899
[conspiratorial] Oh, and FUN fact —

55
00:03:35,899 --> 00:03:40,260
there's a skipped slide lurking at the END of this slide deck too!

56
00:03:41,460 --> 00:03:46,215
[curious] What about the FANCY stuff — math? code? images?

57
00:03:47,415 --> 00:03:49,850
[confidently] MARP has you COVERED.

58
00:03:49,850 --> 00:03:54,860
[excited] Math, syntax-highlighted code, images — all standard Markdown,

59
00:03:54,860 --> 00:03:55,625
no plugins.

60
00:03:55,625 --> 00:03:58,756
And we've got pronunciation dictionaries too,

61
00:03:58,756 --> 00:04:02,722
so names like Dijkstra and Euler ACTUALLY come out right!

62
00:04:03,922 --> 00:04:08,520
[concerned] Doesn't cloud TTS get EXPENSIVE when you're still tweaking things?

63
00:04:09,720 --> 00:04:14,434
[reassuringly] NAH, you don't need cloud for drafting. Use Piper — it's FREE!

64
00:04:14,434 --> 00:04:18,229
runs locally. Throw in the preview flag for a quick rough cut.

65
00:04:18,229 --> 00:04:22,147
[enthusiastic] And the BEST part? slideSonnet caches EVERYTHING!

66
00:04:22,147 --> 00:04:25,759
Change one slide, only THAT slide rebuilds. Fast and cheap!

67
00:04:26,959 --> 00:04:30,120
OK I'm SOLD. [excited] Let's DO this!

68
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:33,685
[warmly] THAT'S what I like to hear!

69
00:04:33,685 --> 00:04:38,022
pip install slidesonnet, write some slides, add your say comments,

70
00:04:38,022 --> 00:04:38,941
and hit build.

71
00:04:38,941 --> 00:04:42,161
[enthusiastic] Now go and make SOMETHING AWESOME!
